docs.abstract: “I knew at some point in time the patent office would recognize” computer software, he said. It happened in 1968, helping to ignite the software market.
docs.snippet: “I knew at some point in time the patent office would recognize” computer software, he said. It happened in 1968, helping to ignite the software market.
docs.lead_paragraph: Martin Goetz, who joined the computer industry in its infancy in the mid-1950s as a programmer working on Univac mainframes and who later received the first U.S. patent for software, died on Oct. 10 at his home in Brighton, Mass. He was 93.

headline.main: Martin Goetz, Who Received the First Software Patent, Dies at 93
headline.print_headline: Martin Goetz, 93, First in U.S. to Earn Software Patent, Dies

docs.abstract: In “The Greatest Capitalist Who Ever Lived,” Ralph Watson McElvenny and Marc Wortman show how Oedipal battles fueled the company’s technological triumphs in the 1960s and beyond.
docs.snippet: In “The Greatest Capitalist Who Ever Lived,” Ralph Watson McElvenny and Marc Wortman show how Oedipal battles fueled the company’s technological triumphs in the 1960s and beyond.
docs.lead_paragraph: Thomas J. Watson Jr. seemed, from a young age, to be destined for failure. Born in 1914, he was an angry and often depressed young boy. Neighbors called him “Terrible Tommy.” He barely gained his high school diploma after attending three different schools. His father, Watson Sr., the head of IBM, was a domineering man who subjected his son to a classic combination of emotional distance and cruelty. Watson Jr. responded by becoming a rebel and wastrel.

headline.main: The Father-Son Struggle That Helped Ensure IBM’s Success
